<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-04-18T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-04-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="1072" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1072">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Austria)/4–1945:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kerinan</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-04-19T00:00:00+03:00">April 19,
                                    1945—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received April 20—12:55
                                p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1273. Claim made by Yugoslav Foreign Office to American, Soviet, British
                            and French representatives at Belgrade for share in Austrian occupation
                            was subject of note addressed April 12 to Molotov<note n="57" xml:id="d1072fn57">Vyacheslav Mikhailovich Molotov, People’s
                                Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> by British
                                Ambassador.<note n="58" xml:id="d1072fn58">Sir Archibald J. K. Clark
                                Kerr.</note> Ambassador states his Government hopes Soviet
                            Government will concur in suggestion that the four powers addressed
                            should jointly reply that claim is inadmissible <pb facs="1328" n="1316" xml:id="pg_1316"/> and concurrently communicate to Yugoslavia terms
                            proposed by Eden<note n="59" xml:id="d1072fn59">Anthony Eden, British
                                Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> at Yalta for
                            settlement of Austro-Yugoslav frontier problem.<note n="60" xml:id="d1072fn60">See <ref target="frus1945Malta#pg_505">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conferences at
                                    Malta and Yalta, 1945, pp. 505</ref> and <ref target="frus1945Malta#pg_887">887</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Repeated to Belgrade as 2, London 170, Paris as 76.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>